Markus Korll, from the German 
financial services group Roland Berger, told Bild: 'During the past few 
months alone more than 10billion euros has been moved abroad.'

Greek
 newspapers have also reported that people flying abroad - including 
nuns, priests and the unemployed - are being stopped at Athens airport 
with suitcases full of euros.

Martin
 Schulz, leader of the Social Democrats in the European Parliament, 
called for the Swiss to impose a 25 per cent tax on the money.

He said: 'In this way we can at least limit this massive flight of capital.

'People secretly moving millions out of the country can't be poor. They must pay their share.

'I can understand why the "little people" are taking to the streets to rebel against this injustice.'

