Bild says that Greek banking bosses have 
already warned the government about the growing panic at bank cash desks
 and the ever-increasing flood of capital abroad.

Government advisers are also warning of 
the dangers of a Northern-Rock style storm outside the banks and the 
need for capital controls, including disconnecting ATM machines, the 
paper reports.

The two-day general strike grounded 
flights, disrupted public transport and shut down everything from shops 
to schools today - as at least 50,000 protesters converged in central 
Athens.

Violent clashes broke out between riot police and protesters near the Greek parliament building, with petrol bombs and rocks being thrown at officers.

